node.text:
Affirmations for us:

You will and can return to yourself.
Healing might feel like it's too much to bear—that's okay. Remember that you are built for it.
Self-love is an act of healing and an act of blooming inside of your body.
If it doesn't elevate or support your growth, I would like you to consider letting it go.

If you feel like you want to give up, hold on a little tighter. If you feel like you can't do it, lean into self-belief a little harder. 

Community, I see you. Share this with whoever you think may need it.

node.text:
This was a challenge for me to learn at one point.

Understanding that I could be a kind and open person and still not want to be friends with everyone felt odd. It felt wrong or mean, almost. 

As I got older, and my circle got smaller, I began to feel more comfortable with being kind and having acquaintances. I no longer use the word friend loosely. I value + nurture my friendships in an intentional way. I was the “call everyone my friend” girl at one point in time because I thought it was negative or rude to not…

The lesson:  It’s not mean for us to not want to cultivate new friendships with everyone we meet, not matter how kind, loving, and welcoming we or they are. It’s not unkind for choosing to not start new a friendship, for whatever reason.

Being a kind person doesn’t mean you have to be friends with everyone. You can still be loving, compassionate, and welcoming w/o feeling like you need to start a new friendship. 

Neutral connections are also okay!
Be kind.
Be authentic.
Respect folks.
Honor your boundaries.

Community: Does anyone else struggle with this—if so why? Really looking forward to the comments here.

If 2021 has taught me anything, it’s taught me that I have a choice. While I am living and breathing and well, the choice is mine.

I’ll be 32 in 5 days. 7/25/89. Whew. I feel really empowered to be in my 30s making choices that that serve my highest self. This is big for me because for years I was convinced that I had no choice or voice. 

It’s been a long LONG long time coming. But as I’ve grown to make self-nurturing a priority, I’ve also evolved into a woman who is becoming more and more confident with intentional self-choosing, care, and deep deep love.

I had a really powerful conversation with @tikasumpter for my @theheygirlpodcast. When we talked about not chasing after things and folks, it reminded me of this note to self that I wrote last year.

As someone who was a chronic “chaser,” intentionally choosing not to be that way was hard. I had to put this into practice after a friend breakup recently and it was really challenging.

But as I continue to grow and do my soul work, I realize and trust that I don’t have to chase after anyone or anything for any reason.

Mantra for the year: Chasing, shrinking, and rejecting myself to be validated is no longer an option for me.

Community: What is no longer an option for you? Leave a comment below. I’d love to read them.

Just in case we needed the reminder this weekend.

Having boundaries doesn’t make you unkind, inconsiderate, or not loving—I know some folks we encounter may create doubt around that.

It’s important that we remember that having and honoring our boundaries gives us a deeper commitment to self that we all deserve.

Honoring my boundaries has offered me so much clarity—and I’m learning not to internalize the projections of those who have a hard time accepting the ones I put into place.

My weekend #affirmation: I am a loving, kind, and considerate person who upholds my boundaries without shame or guilt.

#selfcare / #selflove / #boundaries

Let us always remember: Trauma is not our resting place.

We can heal.
We can grow.
We can shift.
We can transform.

I am learning to not allow my pain to define me. I am learning that my pain points can redirect me toward healing.

I had the honor of being a guest on the @onbeing podcast—and I am still beaming from the moving and thoughtful conversation. I could’ve spoken to Lily, On Being’s executive producer, all day. Our conversation was centered around self-care as community care + generational healing.

You never know who is watching.
You never know whose heart your work will touch.

I hope you stand tall in truth, always.

You can listen to my On Being conversation at the link in my bio—or wherever you stream your podcasts.

#healing / #selflove / #notetoself

node.text:
I am learning to greet the challenging moments in my life with gratitude.

I am learning to let go with unconditional love.

I am learning to give myself and others more grace, even in differences.

Less grudges, more gratitude.
Less judgment, more gratitude.
Less holding to what no longer serves.
More gratitude in the letting go.

I’ve been deep in an intentional gratitude practice since November and it’s shifting how I move through the world and my relationships. It’s changing my life.

Swipe through for some comfort if you’re struggling with letting go or if you need a reminder when parting ways feels hard.

If you’re wanting a deeper dive into gratitude practice and writing as meditation—join me for my year long (YES, a whole year) gratitude mediation series with @ritualapp. I’m teaching how to weave grateful living into our daily lives by way of writing practice. Week 1 is out now, it’s free, and you can learn more at the link in my bio.

#selflove / #selfcare / #growth
